At most elections of modern times, the rule is that the north belongs to Labour and the south to the Tories and the bits of each that don't are scooped up by the Lib Dems or Nationalists. Mrs Thatcher's long-term legacy to her party was to turn the great cities of the north into electoral wastelands for the Tories. Tony Blair's magic had gone by his late period and Labour support in the south collapsed altogether once the party dumped him for the Scottish Gordon Brown.
